  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_3_footnotes
  sourcePage 3
obj_root_law_sections_3_content:
  string
  line 3
  line `( iv ) any false claim is made for the quality prescribed for its grade designation, u pon the label`
  line `or through advertisement or in any other manner.]`
  line `3. Prescription of grade designation s. — 1 [( 1 ) ] The Central Government may, after previous`
  line `publication by notification in the Official Gazette, 2 [make rules to carry out the provisions of this Act.`
  line `( 2 ) In particular, and without prejudice to the generality of the foregoing power, such rules may`
  line `provide for all or any of the following matters, namely: — ]`
  line `( a ) fixing grade designations to indicate the quality of any scheduled article;`
  line `( b ) defining the quality indicated by every grade designation;`
  line `( c ) specifying grade designation marks to represent particular grade designations;`
  line `( d ) authorising a person or a body of persons, subject to any prescribed conditions, to mark with a`
  line `grade designation mark any article in respect of which such mark has been prescribed or any covering`
  line `containing or label attached to any such article;`
  line `( e ) specifying the conditions referred to in clause ( d ) including in respect of any article`
  line `conditions as to the manner of mar king, the manner in which the article shall be packed, the type of`
  line `covering to be used, and the quantity by weight, number or otherwise to be included in each covering;`
  line `( f ) providing for the payment of any expenses incurred in connection with the manufactu re or use`
  line `of any implement necessary for the reproduction of a grade designation mark or with the manufacture`
  line `or use of any covering or label marked with a grade designation mark 3 [or with measures for the`
  line `control of the quality of articles marked with gra de designation marks including testing of samples`
  line `and inspection of such articles or with any publicity work carried out to promote the sale of any class`
  line `of such articles;] 4 ***`
  line `( g ) providing for the confiscation and disposal of produce marked otherwise than in accordance`
  line `with the prescribed conditions with a grade designation mark;`
  line `5 [ ( ga ) holding inquiry and imposing penalty under s ub - s ection ( 1 ) of s ection 5C;`
  line `( gb ) preferring appeal under s ub - s ection ( 1 ) of s ection 5D; ]`
  line `6 [( h ) any other matter which is required to be, or may be, prescribed.]`
  line `7 [ 8 [ ( 3 )] Every rule made by the Central Government under this Act shall be laid, as soon as may be`
  line `after it is made, before each House of Parliament, while it is in session, for a total period of thirty days`
  line `which ma y be comprised in one session or in two or more successive sessions, and if, before the expiry of`
  line `the session immediately following the session or the successive sessions aforesaid, both Houses agree in`
  line `making any modification in the rule or both Houses ag ree that the rule should not be made, the rule shall`
  line `thereafter have effect only in such modified form or be of no effect, as the case may be; so, however, that`
  line `any such modification or annulment shall be without prejudice to the validity of anything previ ously done`
  line `under that rule.]`
  line `1. Section 3 re - numbered as sub - section ( 1 ) thereof by Act 20 of 1983, s. 2 and the Schedule (w.e.f. 15 - 3 - 198 4 ).`
  line `2. Subs. by Act 76 of 1986, s. 3, for “make rules — ” (w.e.f. 15 - 4 - 1987).`
  line `3. Ins. by Act 20 of 1943, s. 2 (w.e.f. 13 - 8 - 1943).`
  line `4. The word “and” omitted by Act 76 of 1986, s. 3 (w.e.f. 15 - 4 - 1987).`
  line `5. Ins. by Act 18 of 2023, s. 2 and the Schedule (w.e.f. 31 - 7 - 2024).`
  line `6. Ins. by Act 76 of 1986, s. 3 (w.e.f. 15 - 4 - 1987).`
  line `7. Ins. by Act 20 of 1983, s. 2 and the Schedule (w.e.f. 15 - 3 - 198 4 ).`
  line `8. Sub - section ( 2 ) re - numbered as sub - section ( 3 ) thereof by Act 76 of 1986, s. 3 (w.e.f. 15 - 4 - 1987).`
obj_root_law_sections_3_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_4:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-4
  sectionNo (4)
  orderNo 4
  title `Page 4`
  content obj_root_law_sections_4_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_4_footnotes
  sourcePage 4
obj_root_law_sections_4_content:
  string
  line 4
  line `1 [ 3A. Powers of entry, inspection and search. — ( 1 ) Any officer of the Central Government or a`
  line `State Government or any authority, being an officer of a gazette drank or of equivalent rank, authorised`
  line `by the Central government may, if he has reason to believe that any provision of t his Act or the rules`
  line `made there under has been, or is being, contravened, enter any premises at any reasonable time and make`
  line `necessary inspection of, and search for, the agri cultural produce in relation to which such contravention`
  line `has been, or is being, made.`
  line `( 2 ) Every authorisation made under sub - section ( 1 ) shall be deemed to be a warrant referred to`
  line `in s ection 93 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973 (2 of 1974).`
  line `3B. Powers of the authorised officer to seize agricultural produce. — ( 1 ) An officer authorised`
  line `under sub - section ( 1 ) of Section 3A may seize and detain any agricultural produce in relation to which an`
  line `offence under this Act or the rules made t hereunder is being, or appears to have been, committed, or`
  line `which is intended or likely to be used in the commission of such offe nce:`
  line `Provided that where any agricultural produce seized under this sub - section is subject to speedy or`
  line `natural decay, the officer so authorised may dispose of such produce in such manner as may be`
  line prescribed.
  line `( 2 ) The provisions of s ection 102 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973 (2 of 1974) shall apply to`
  line `every seizure made under this section. ]`
  line `4. Penalty for unauthorised marking with grade designation mark. — Whoever marks`
  line `any scheduled article with a grade designation mark, not being authorised to do so by rule made under`
  line `s ection 3, shall be 2 [ liable to penalty not exceeding five lakh rupees ].`
  line `5. Penalty for counterfeiting grade designation mark. — Whoever counterfeits any gr ade`
  line `designation mark or has in his possession any die, plate or other instrument for the purpose of`
  line `counterfeiting a grade designation mark shall be 3 [ liable to penalty not exceeding fifteen lakh rupees ].`
  line `4 [ 5A. Penalty for selling migra t ed articles. — Whoever sells any scheduled article which is migra t ed`
  line `shall be 5 [ liable to penalty not exceeding three lakh rupees ].`
  line `5B. Power to prescribe compulsory grade designations in respect of certain articles. — ( 1 ) Where`
  line `the Central Government is of opinion that it is necessary in the public interest or for the protection of`
  line `consumers that any scheduled article or class of articles shall not be sold or distributed except after such`
  line `article or class of articles is marked with the grade designation mark, it may, by no tification in the Official`
  line `Gazette, make a declaration to that effect.`
  line `( 2 ) Any notification issued under sub - section ( 1 ) shall specify the area or areas in relation to which`
  line `the notification shall have effect.`
  line `( 3 ) Where a notification under sub - section ( 1 ) is issued in respect of any area or areas, no person shall`
  line `sell or offer to sell or distribute or offer to distribute any scheduled article or class thereof in the area or`
  line `areas except in accordance with the provisions of t his Act or the rules made there under.`
  line `( 4 ) Whoever contravenes the provisions of this section shall be 6 [ liable to penalty not exceeding five`
  line `lakh rupees ].`
  line `1. Ins. by Act 76 of 1986, s. 4 ( w.e.f. 15 - 4 - 1987 ).`
  line `2. Subs. by Act 18 of 2023, s. 2 and the Schedule for certain words (w.e.f. 31 - 7 - 2024).`
  line `3. Subs. by s. 2 and the Schedule, ibid., for certain words (31 - 7 - 2024).`
  line `4. Ins. by Act 76 of 1986, s. 7 (w.e.f. 15 - 4 - 1987).`
  line `5. Subs. by Act 18 of 2023, s. 2 and the Schedule for certain words (31 - 7 - 2024).`
  line `6. Subs. by s. 2 and the Schedule, ibid., for certain words (w.e.f. 31 - 7 - 2024).`
obj_root_law_sections_4_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_5:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-5
  sectionNo (5)
  orderNo 5
  title `Page 5`
  content obj_root_law_sections_5_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_5_footnotes
  sourcePage 5
obj_root_law_sections_5_content:
  string
  line 5
  line `1 [ 5C. Adjudicating officer. — ( 1 ) The Central Government may, for the purposes of determining the`
  line `penalties under sections 4, 5, 5A and 5B, appoint an officer not below the rank of Deputy Secretary to the`
  line `Government of India or an officer not below the rank of Deputy Secretary to the State Government, to be`
  line `adjudicating officer to hold an inquiry and impose penalty, in the manner as ma y be prescribed:`
  line `Provided that the Central Government may appoint as many adjudicating officers as may be required.`
  line `( 2 ) The adjudicating officer may summon and enforce the attendance of any person acquainted with`
  line `the facts and circumstances of the case to give evidence or to produce any document, which in the opinion`
  line `of the adjudicating officer, may be useful for, or relevant to, the subject - matter of the inquiry and if, on`
  line `such inquiry, he is satisfied that the person concerned has failed to comply with th e provisions of`
  line `sections 4, 5, 5A and 5B, he may impose penalty:`
  line `Provided that no such penalty shall be imposed without giving the person concerned a reasonable`
  line `opportunity of being heard in the matter.`
  line `5D. Appeal. — ( 1 ) Whoever aggrieved by the order, passed by the adjudicating officer under Section`
  line `5C may prefer an appeal to the Agricultural Marketing Adviser, Government of India within thirty days`
  line `from the date of receipt of order in such manner as may be prescribed.`
  line `( 2 ) An app eal may be admitted after the expiry of the period of thirty days if the appellant satisfies the`
  line `Agricultural Marketing Adviser that he had sufficient cause for not preferring the appeal within that`
  line period.
  line `( 3 ) The Agricultural Marketing Adviser may, after giving the parties to the appeal an opportunity of`
  line `being heard, pass such order as he may think fit.`
  line `( 4 ) The Agricultural Marketing Adviser referred to in s ub - s ection ( 1 ) shall dispose of the appeal`
  line `within sixty days from the date of filing.`
  line `5E. Recovery. — Notwithstanding anything contained in this Act, if penalty imposed by the`
  line `adjudicating officer under Section 5C or order of the Agricultural Marketing Adviser under Section 5D,`
  line `as the case may be, is not deposited, the amount shall be recovered as an arr ear of land revenue. ]`
  line `6. Extension of application of Act. — The Central Government, after such consultation as it thinks fit`
  line `of the interests likely to be affected, may by notification in the Official Gazette declare that the provisions`
  line `of this Act shall app ly to an article of agricultural produce not included in the Schedule 2 [or to an article`
  line `other than an article of agricultural produce] and on the publication of such notification such article shall`
  line `be deemed to be included in the Schedule.`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 18 of 2023, s. 2 and the Schedule for section 5C (w.e.f. 31 - 7 - 2024).`
  line `2. Ins. by Act 13 of 1942, s. 3 (w.e.f. 24 - 2 - 1937 ).`
obj_root_law_sections_5_footnotes:
  string
  line
